ce:section.ce:para:
The FT-IR spectra of the PEI N-doped GQDs and AgNPs/PEI N-doped GQDs nanocomposites exhibit characteristic changes in the functional group frequencies when compared with the spectrum of the starting materials PEI N-doped GQDs (
                           Fig. S1
                        ). The OH + NH2 + NH + COOH, C–H, CO, C-N, CC, and C-O vibration bands are observed at 3433, 2931, 1702, 1655, 1557, and 1302 cm−1 of starting materials GQDs, respectively. In the PEI N-doped GQDs spectrum, OH + NH2 + NH + COOH bands overlap. For AgNPs/PEI N-doped GQDs nanocomposites, the OH, NH2, NH, C–H, C-N, CC, and C-O vibration bands are observed at 3468, 3378, 3217, 2981, 1653, 1554, and 1385 cm−1, respectively (
                           Fig. S2
                        ). The frequency of the OH, NH2, and NH bonds shifted to higher values​​ in the AgNPs/PEI N-doped GQDs nanocomposites. Interestingly, when compared to GQDs, the intensity of the carboxyl absorption bands at 1702 cm−1 decreases in the FT-IR spectrum of the AgNPs/PEI N-doped GQDs nanocomposite (
                           Fig. S2
                        ). These results show that Ag is reduced to form AgNPs by COOH groups on the AgNPs/PEI N-doped GQDs nanocomposite surfaces, and that the COOH groups are converted to CO2 groups after the reaction. A new band for AgNPs/PEI N-doped GQDs nanocomposite appeared at 1763 cm in the FTIR spectrum. This band indicates that OH groups are oxidized to ketone groups.
